Project Description

This project demonstrates a bio-signal controlled robotic hand using EMG (Electromyography) and EEG (Electroencephalography) signals. The system uses the BioAmp EXG Pill to amplify extremely small electrical signals generated by muscle activity or brain signals. These signals are captured using gel electrodes, processed by an ESP32 microcontroller, and used to control the movement of a robotic hand.

The goal of the project was to explore human–machine interaction using bio-signals, where muscle contractions or neural signals can directly control robotic actuators. The ESP32 reads the amplified signals from the EXG Pill, processes them using threshold-based signal detection, and generates control commands for the robotic hand.

The system can detect muscle activation patterns (EMG) such as finger or wrist contraction, and translate them into movement commands like open and close of the robotic hand.

This project explores concepts in:

Bio-signal acquisition

Biomedical signal amplification

Embedded signal processing

Human–machine interfaces

Assistive robotics
